{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170963/1937111101/0629.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL NEWS\nThe Business Trend\nSecession Not, Checked\nThe week brought no indication that\na turning point had been reached in\nthe downward movement of business.\nRailroad car loadings registered a\ntemporary stability or even an ad\nvance, as measured in the indexes,\nbut the previous week's decline was\nperhaps disproportionately severe.\nThe stock market was no longer\nbuoyed up by the stimulating in\nfluence of the Federal Reserve board's\nreduction of margin requirements\u2014or\nrather combined reduction and in\ncrease, for the higher margin against\nshort sales, whether or not theoreti\ncally desirable, had the probable im\nmediate effect of forcing the shorts to\ncover and thus boosting prices for the\ntime being.\nBonds, which had recorded a slight\nbut fairly consistent recovery since\nOctober 19, exhibited yielding tend\nencies. Commodity prices carried on\nthe decline of previous weeks. Cotton\nprices showed more resistance, but\nwheat responded to weakness in world\nmarkets and, especially, to the lack of\nforeign demand for American cash\nofferings. Domestic copper, which\nearly in the year was selling for 17\ncents, ts now at 11, without, certainly\nthat the bottom has been reached.\nThis decline affords a measure of the\nextent to which the international com\nmodity inflation of the early part of\n1937 has been flattened out.\nCoffee took a spectacular plunge\nwhen the Brazilian government an\nnounced abandonment of its price\ncontrol program. If a slump in coffee\nwere all that American buyers of raw\nmaterial had to worry about, the out\nlook would be sunny. But the decline\nIn commodities is widespread, and\nmanufacturers and merchants are\nreluctant to make commitments until\nan approach to stability is in sight.\nOn the other hand, the Annalist's in\nclusive index of commodity prices still\nstands 4V4 points higher than at the\nsame time a year ago.\nPrice Problems\nThe nation\u2019s recovery movement\nhas thus been arrested by two op\nposite tendencies: Higher prices and\ndeclining prices. If the price move\nment now were wholly downward,\nthere would be reason to look for a\nrapid upturn in business as soon as\nconsumers\u2019 needs began to prevail\nover the present buying hesitancy.\nBut in the durable goods industries\nproduction costs have been pegged\nat the highest levels in history by\nwage agreements and increasing taxes,\nand manufacturers are unable or re\nluctant to offer price concessions.\nMany workers who rejoiced at receiv\ning higher w'ages are finding that\ntheir weekly earnings are less than a\nyear ago\u2014w'hich is exactly what cau\ntious economists predicted in case\ncosts were forced up too rapidly.\nThe recent slump in raw' material\nprices has an unsettling effect on pro\nduction precisely because no one dares\nto order large stocks while the decline\nis going on. It is possible that some\ndegree of stability in cotton and wool\nprices will be attained soon, with re\nsulting stimulus to production and\ntrade. In the meantime every declin\ning tendency reinforces every other.\nIn addition to price uncertainty, re\ntail lines are hampered by the heavy\ninventories which an expectation of\nhigher prices and possibly an over\nestimate of public buying power\ncaused them to store up earlier this\nyear.\nIncentives Seeded\nIn view of the need of fresh incen\ntives that will stimulate basic indus\ntries the committee of utility execu-\nfives has chosen an opportune time j\nfor urging the government to adopt\na policy that will promote investment\nand consequent construction activity\nin the utility industry. Practically all\neconomists agree that the causes\nwhich ordinarily produce a serious\ndepression are lacking, and it is un\ndesirable that matters which are ca\npable of adjustment should be allowed\nto make a moderate recession more\nserious than need be. For this reason\nsome observers still expect that some\nrevision of tax laws will be favored\nby Congress as a preventive measure.\nThe country is getting one illustra\ntion after another of the fact that\nbusiness will overcome any artiflcally\nimposed handicaps when it is advanc\ning but may suffer an undue burden\nwhen it is declining. Speaking of mar\ngin requirements in stock trading,\nA. D. Noyes of the New York Times\nsaid a week ago that \"there was no\nevidence that the Reserve board's\nmarking-up of maximum margins in\nFebruary, 1936, had affected the\nmarket's course.\u201d The same may be J\nsaid of money rates in any period\nwhen the market is in the throes of a I\nwild advance.\nThe same principle also applies to\ngeneral business in the matter of\ntaxes or wage costs. When volumi\nnous orders and profits are in sight\nany burden is quickly assumed, even\nif apprehension is felt as to its ulti\nmate consequences. Government reg\nulation that merely complicates busi\nness in any advancing period may\nprove unduly deflationary in a decline.\nWEEKLY REVIEW\nOF BOND MARKET\nNew York. Nov. 7 (AP)\u2014The\nclouded business outlook and in\ndustry\u2019s slackening puce were re\nflected In thin and nervous bond\nmarkets last week. The trend was\ndown on dwindling volume as the\ngeneral Investing public shunned the\nmarket place.\nIjOwer priced corporate obligations\nfollowed an uninterrupted downward\ncourse and were joined to some ex\ntent by higher priced liens as evi\ndenced by their standing In the\naverages as the session ended.\nThe carrier group found the hard\nest going. Such issues as St Paul 6s,\nErie 6s, Illinois Central 4%s and\nBaltimore A Ohio 4tjs were targets\nfor selling. Reduced profit margins\nas a result of Increased taxes and\nwages together with curtailed traffic\ndarkened the rail outlook, some ob\nservers said.\nA little encouragement was afforded\nby the carriers petition for an In\ncrease In rail freight rates which re\nceived the hacking of a number of\nshipping and labor groups but It\nwas generally believed in financial\nCircles that a decision would not be\nforthcoming for at least 90 days.\nOther corporate Issues went down\nhill With the steel operating rate\nsinking below .\u2019>o per cent of capacity\nand other business Indices pointing\nBUSINESS ANSWERS\nCHALLENGE TO PUT\nITS HOUSE IN ORDER\nCommittee of Manufactur\ners\u2019 Group Outlines Princi\nples, Asks Private Enter\nprise Prove Its Worth\nNew York, Nov, 1 (AP) A\ndeclaration of principles, calling on\nbusiness to maintain high ethical\nstandards, and described as \u201ca direct\nanswer to those who challenge In\nj rtustry to pilf its own house in order.\u201d\nwas made public today by the com\nmittee on industrial practices of the\nNational Association of Manufac\nturers.\nThe report, which was approved by\nthe board of directors of the associa\ntion, will be submitted for adoption\nby the congress of American indus\ntry, to be held here early in Decem\nber.\n\"It is the obligation of every indus\ntrial enterprise to survey its business\npractices, to analyze points of weak\nness and points of strength, to\ndemonstrate its capacity for change\nwhere necessary, and to adopt and\nmaintain high ethical standards in all\nits operations,\u201d the report said.\nPrivate Enterprise \u201cEndangered\u201d\nAsserting that private enterprise is\nendangered, the report continued:\n\"The American private enterprise\nsystem, founded on the theory that\nindividuals are different In ability and\naccomplishment: based in practice on\nthe principles of private property and\nspecial reward for special achieve\nment, Is threatened.\n\u201cTo a greater and greater degree\na constant and deliberate effort is\nbeing made to supersede private en\nterprise with vast stats controls\nwhich progressively continued, ulti\nmately will emerge as state social\nism.\u201d\nCalls of Proof of Worth\nThe committee recommended that\nprivate enterprise and private prop\nerty demonstrate their worth to the\npublic and the desirability of their\nperpetuation by:\u2014\n\u201c1. Informing the public as to the\naccomplishments of the American\nprivate enterprise system;\n\"2. Exposing to the public the\nfallacies of proposals to abolish or\ncripple the American private enter\nprise system;\n\u201c3. Adherence by all business to\nwell-tested and high principles of\nconduct.\u201d\nINVESTMENT MEN\nPLAN AGGRESSIVE\nLEGISLATIVE STAND\nAssociation to Tighten Up\nMembership Requirements\n\u2014Harvard Teacher Notes\n\u2018Essential Objectives\u2019\nWhite Sulphur Springs. W. Va..\nNov. s\u2014(AP> \u2014The Investment Bank\ners association launched a dual pro\ngram today to take \"a progressive\nand aggressive stand\" in matters of\nj legislation, and to make membership\nin the association \"a badge of integ\nj rlty and worth.\u201d\nIts board of governors announced to\nits annual convention a redrafting of\nthe association's constitution and by\nlaws, involving a drastic tightening\nup of membership requirements, and\na strengthening of its executive per\nsonnel.\nAt the same time, two speakers\nbefore the day\u2019s sessions looked to\nWashington for solutions to the prob\nlem of the present slump in the se\ncurities markets, which has brought\nthe investment hankers' business nf\nraising capital for industry almost\nto a standstill.\nEdward B. Hall of Chicago, presi\ndent of the association, said it was\nno more fair now to blame the cur\nrent slump on the government than\nit was to blame the 1929-32 decline\non the investment bankers.\nLack of Confidence Seen\nBut he described the recent tumble\nin securities as definitely reflecting a\nlack of confidence in the future of\nbusiness, and said the administration\ncould do much to restore it by re\nvising the capital gains and undivided\nprofits taxes, by improving the finan\ncial situation of the railroads and con\ndition affecting the utilities, and in\ngeneral \"maintaining conditions un\nder which business can function and\nmeet its payrolls and provide a re\nturn on the capital which will serve\nas a stimulus to further savings.\"\nDr John H. Williams, professor of\neconomics at Harvard and vice-pres\nident of the New York Federal Re\nserve Bank, the second speaker, said,\n\u201cas matters now stand, probably no\nj one can say with entire confidence\nj whether we are facing a minor or a\ni major depression,\" but he was hope\nful of early resumption of the re\ncovery (rend, through encouragement\nof private investment.\nEssential Objectives\nThe Harvard economist explained\nthe essential recovery objectives as\nremoval of obstacles to investment In\nutilities, housing, railroads, and gen\neral plant and equipment; removal of\npossible defects in the tax system,\nwith special reference to the undis-\nI triha ted profits, capital gains, and se\ncurlty taxes; and curing of possible\ni defects in the government regulations\nfor securities markets.\nto curtailment In many linos, in\ndustrial obligations found a precari\nous footing. Offerings were at no time\nheavy but the trend was lower.\nUtility Hens came off a little better\nthan other groups although un\ncertainty and apprehension as to what\nthe coming special session of Congress\nmight hold in the way of legislation\nfor the power Industry loomed large\nin some financial quarters.\nMany traders apparently held little\nfaith in the widely circulated rumor*\nCongress might revise drastically the\ncapital gains and surplus profit*\ntaxes and open the way for a general\nresumption of new financing. The\nnew capital market has almost\nreached the vanishing point and in\ndications are that there will be little\nImprovement In the near future.\nFederal loans pursued a slightly\nhigher (uturse. Fluctuations were ex\ntremely narrow and volume was small\nIn spite of reports hanks and other\nInstitutions were buying governments.\nForeign dollar issues were in\nspasmodic demand and ended the\nweek slightly higher In the averages.\n.Japanese and Polish obligations re\ncorded modest gains and Italian loans\nwere fairly active but not much\nchanged.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY. NOVEMBER 11, 1937\nMarket Slump Being Studied\nFor Manipulation Evidence\nTwentieth Century Fund to Probe Effect of Short\nSale* at Request of Exchange Hopes to Find\nWhether Recession Was Deliberately Engineered\nBy JOHN REAR\nNew York, Nov. *\u2014(AP) \u2014The big\ngest \u201cbear\u201d hunt in the history of\nWall street was on tonight in an ef\nfort to learn whether the current\nstock market slump was deliberately\nmanipulated.\nIt was undertaken by the Twen\ntieth Century fund\u2014an independent,\nendowed foundation which has been\ncritical of market practices in the\npast\u2014at the request of the stock ex\nchange.\nThe investigation will run most of\nthe winter, with a corps of perhaps\n30 expert auditors digging deep into\nthe records of \"short\u201d sales and what\ncfWK.*'tb.\u00ab.*t \"ttea.c '-tyM'WS.ft** WivJV\non falling prices.\nThe results will be published, the\nfund promised, \"no matter what they\nmay be.\u201d It added:\n\"The public, as well as the ex\nchange and its members, should know\nto what degree and in what ways\nshort, selling operations have affected\nthe drastic decline in security values\nduring recent months.\u201d\nSampling Process\nThe sharpest economic brains of\nthe country were asked to direct the\nInquiry, which under present plans\nwill follow a scientific sampling pro\ncess. The most active stock issues,\nboth on the rising and the failing\nmarket, will be studied Intensively.\nThe investigators will And out who\nsold what, how much, when, and how\nmuch profit he made.\nAny hints, dug up in this way, that\nbearish speculators forced the market\ndown will be followed through, wher\never they may lead.\nThe operations of the \"bears\" have\nnever before been scrutinized on such\na scale. The stock market itself does\nnot know what effect \"short selling\"\nhas, so it asked the fund to find out.\nThe exchange's request for the in\nvestigation. transmitted to the fund\nby letter on October 28, was the first\nsuch request the exchange ever made\nto an outside. Independent agency.\nThe request covered only \"the effects\nof short selling.\" The fund's accept\nance, transmitted by letter to Charles\nR. Gay, president of the exchange,\nwas on the same basis.\nHow Short Selling Works\n\"Short\" selling, or \"bear\" trading,\nis the practice of selling stocks \u2014be-\nfore you actually own them\u2014on the\ngamble that the price will fall. Here\nis how it works:\nYou are a speculator. You look\nover tiic stock quotations and pick out\na stock whose price you think is too\nhigh, the quotation is, perhaps, $150:\nyou think the real value Is about SIOO,\nand that sooner or later the price\nwill drop. So you go to a broker and\ntell him \u201csell 100 shares of so-and\nso stock short.\u201d The broker sells the\nstock for $15,000. You do not have the\nstock, but you must deliver it in\ntwo days so you go to what Wall\nstreet knows as the \"loan crowd\u201d and\nborrow the 100 shares. These you de\nliver to the buyer, and you collect\nthe $15,000. Then yotl wait for the\nstock to go down. If it goes down to\nSIOO, you take SIO,OOO of your $15.-\n000 and buy 100 shares. You give\nthese back to the fellow who loaned\nthem to you, and pocket SSOOO profit.\nIf the stock goes up instead of down,\nyou lose money.\n\"Short\u201d sellers defend this practice\non the grounds that it balances the\nmarket against margin traders,\nspeculators who buy on the gamble\nthat prices will rise. Opponents of\nshort\u201d, selling blame it for deepening\nmarket slumps.\n\u201cFinal anti Complete\nRumors of \"short\u201d manipulations In\nthe market's current case of fidgets\nmake the fund's investigation \"both\nimportant and timely,\u201d Evans Clark,\ndirector of the. Twentieth century\nfund, said in today's letter to Gay.\nThe letter said a \u201cfinal and com\nplete\u201d study of all \"short\" transac\ntions would be impossible because of\nthe immense scope of the. task, so\nthe scientific sampling method would\nbe adopted.\nThe letter rejected an exchange of\nfer of financial aid in the investiga\ntion, explaining: \u201cIt is the fund's\npolicy to meet expenses of such\nstudies exclusively from its own\nfunds.\u201d\nAssembling of the original records\non which the inquiry will be based\nwas left, however, to the exchange.\nIn these records is a great mass of\nconfidential data to which the fund j\nwill have access with but one restric-\ntion: No names of individuals will be\npublished by the fund.\nThe committee of economists and j\nbusiness leaders who will direct the\ninvestigation is now being chosen, and j\nthe actual digging into the records\nwill start soon.\n1938 Investigation by EnnS\nThe stock market is not new to in\nvestigations by the Twentieth Century j\nfund. In 1933, hefore the security ex-\nchange commission was established, a\nstudy was made of trading in gen- j\nCLASS 1 RAILWAYS\nASK 15 PER CENT\nFREIGHT RATE RISE\nEastern Roads Ask Increase\nin Passenger Fares and\nTruck Concerns \u2018Plan to\nRequest Higher Rates'\nWashington, Nov. s\u2014The nation\u2019s\nclass 1 railroads today petitioned the\nInterstate Commerce commission for\nan immediate 15 per cent horizontal\nrate Increase on all freight except\nfive classes of perishables.\nAt the same time, eastern roads re\nquested a boost from 2 to 3.5 cents\na mile on passenger coach fares.\nSouthern and western carriers already\nhave revised passenger tariffs tip\nward wdthln limits authorized by the\n1. C. C.\nIn a statement coincident with the\npetitions, President J. J. Pelley of the\nAssociation of American Railroads\nsaid wages, higher taxes and rising\nmaterial cotta have placed the car\nriers in a \"critical condition.\u201d He\nasserted;\n\"Unless this situation is met\npromptly by an increase In their\nrevenues, their ability to furnish the\nkind of transportation service that\nindustry and agriculture demand will\nbe impaired.\"\nCites Increases In Costs\nPelley declared that since 1932 ma\nterials have advanced 40 per cent:\nwages, 18 per cent; and taxes, Includ\ned social security levies. 25 per cent.\nIn contrast, he said, average freight\nratea were cut 10 per cent and aver\nage passenger fares, 1* per cent.\nAn appendix to the petition fixed\nnet. operating Income for the 12\nmontha ending last June 30 at $728.-\n583.000\u2014\"harely sufficient to meet\npetitioners' Axed charges of $841,000,-\n000 for that year.\"\neral, A number of proposals made by\nthe fund then have since been car\nried out by the SEC. Among these\nwere the margin requirements on both\n\"long\u201d and \"short\u201d selling.\nThe fund\u2019s stand on \"short\" sell\ning as a results of the limited eurvey\nmade in that field in 1933 was that,\nalthough they generally were unim\nportant, \"bear\u201d maneuvers sharply\ndepress prices when engaged in on a\nlarge scale at sudden Intervals. It\nwas'recommended that restrictions be\nplaced on the amount of \"short\u201d\ntransactions in a single day, and that\nheavy \"dumping\" of \"short\" holdings\nr fee orekthivi'i,\nAny findings the present study\nbrings will carry the weight of a trus\ntee's board which includes such prom\ninent figures as Roscoe Pound, foi\nmer dean of the Harvard law school;\nCharles P. Taft, son of the former\npresident, one of the advisers to Alf\nM. Landon in the last presidential\nelection, and a mediator in the big\nsteel strike; Robert H. Jackson, as\nsistant attorney general of the United\nStates; John H. Fahey, head of the\nHome Owners' Loan corporation;\nFrancis Biddle, former chairman of\nthe national labor board; Robert S.\nLynd, author of the sociological novel,\n\u201cMiddletown\u201d; and leading writers :/(d\nindustrialists.\nStick to T\u00bbx Collecting\nHe suggested the federal govern\ni ment restrict its welfare activities to\nj the function of tax collecting. The\nj alcoholic beverages, tobacco, excise\nand social security taxes, he ex-\nI plained, would net revenue of some\nj $2,500,000,000 annually and could be\nmore efficiently collected by the feder\nal government than local units. If\nthese taxes were apportioned among\nthe states on a population or other\nagreed basis, he thought they could\nthen readily meet, their welfare re\nquirements. He pointed out that cen\ntralized tax collection of this nature\nis now being done successfully in\nArgentina.\nFOREIGN CAPITAL\nREPATRIATED; GOLD\nFLOW REVERSED\n\nEuropean Currencies at\nTheir Highest Levels in\nMore Than Year in Terms\nof American Dollar\nNew York, Nov. B\u2014(AP)\u2014Repatria\ntion of foreign capital, which had\nbeen placed in this country for in\nvestment and safe keeping, today\nforced European currencies to their\nhighest levels in more than a year,\nin terms of the dollar, and brought\nabout a complete reversal in the\nflow of gold.\nAs the money-holders of Europe\nsold dollar balances held in this\ncountry and bought currencies of\nother countries, the pound sterling\nrose 1% cents to $5.03%, in com\nj parison with a normal relationship\nwith the dollar of around st.BB to the\nj pound.\nThe French franc was .01% higher,\nthe Belgian betgs ,03 of a cent, the\nNetherlands guilder .06 and the Swiss\nfranc .01.\nGovernment control funds were\nbusy trying to hold down the fluctua\ntions. One example of this was the\nannouncement at Washington by\nSecretary of the Treasury Morgen\nthau that $10,250,000 in gold would\nleave Wednesday for France \u2014the\nfirst export of gold from this coun\ntry in more than two years.\nThe price of gold at London\u2014as a\nresult of the clamor by foreign in\nvestors who wanted something safe\nto put their money in after with\ndrawing balances held in this coun\ntry\u2014reached the equivalent of $35,23\nan ounce.\nBANKERS ARE TOLD\nOF FINANCING NEED\nBY PUBLIC UTILITIES\nRequirement of 10 Billion\nMay Be Faced \u2014Federal\nSpokesman Asks Support\nfor Utility Regulation\nWhite Sulphur Springs, W. Va\u201e\nNov 4 \u2014(P) \u2014The prospect that sec\nurity underwriters may be called up\non to finance some $10,000,000,000 in\npublic utility requirements in the\nnext few years was put before the\nannual convention of the Investment\nBankers' association today.\nThe bankers, who are seeking\nmeans of reopening the gates to new\ncapital through issuance of securities,\ntemporarily shut by the autumn\nslump in the stock and bond mar\nkets, heard an appeal for support, of\nutility regulation by an administra\ntion spokesman and complaint that\naome of the government controla were\nunnecessarily drastic by a power\ncompany president.\nMcNlnlch Aska Support\nFrank R. McNinich. sharp-featured\nformer chairman of the Federal Pow\ner commission, said:\n\u201cI appeal to you, whose advice Is\nvery often the determining factor in\nthe investment of large sums of\nmoney by the people of this coun\ntry. to give your active support to\nregulatory' legislation and to give\nyour constructive help and coopera\ntion toward overcoming the defeatist\nattitude of some utility executives.\"\nAlex Dow, whits-whiskered 76-year\nold president of the Detroit Edison\ncompany, said he differed with Mc-\nNinich more In degree than in di\nrection, but turned hla fire upon the\npublic utility holding company act,\nsaying:\n\"Why wipe out a whole class of\nsiructures honest and otherwise, to\npetmit conirol, or possibly punishment\nof some offenders? I give it up.\u201d\nHe also criticised the cost account\ning procedures of the TVA yardstick\nas a \"setup\" which no memlter of\nthe bankers' association would ac\ncept as a basts for a security offer\ning\nMcNinch recited detailed statistics\nto show that the utility industry was\nprospering under government control,\nand held up the public utility act of\n]9ss as bulwark of strength In\nthe power Industry\" which had re\nstored confidence of Investors, and\nwhich should facilitate financing.\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nNew York Stock exchange..\nNew York Curb market 2IMOO\nBouton Stock exchange Ib,AH\nSTOCK AIVKRAOKS\n[Compiled by the Ae&ociated Preen J\nSO IS 15 00\nInd. Rails Util. Btke.\nKK change 1.2 +.7\nTuesday 04.2 21.9 S4.S 40.\u00ab\nPrcvlooh day 03.0 21.4 33.0 43.1\nMonth ago 72.3 24.1 .34.5 50.0\nYear ago tM 41.1 v 51.7 72.7\n1937 high 191.0 49.5 54.0 75.3\n1937 low 03.0 20.7 31.0 45.1\n1930 high 99.3 43.5 53.7 72. K\n1930 low 73.4 *0.2 43.4 55.7\nMovement In Recent Years\n1932 low 17.5 3.7 23.9 10.9\n1929 high 140.9 153.9 134.3 157.7\n1927 low 51.0 95.3 01.8 01.3\nNew York v *2. --4 P,'\nwere in the stock market for utility,\ncopper and steel shares today and\nleading issues finished fractions to\n2 points higher.\nWhat was interpreted as a more\nconciliatory attitude of the SEC to\nward utility companies stimulated\nconsiderable interest in this group\nand possibility of modification of the\ncapital gains and undistributed prof\nits imports, at the coming session of\nCongress, attracted day-to-day trad\ners to the general list.\nA sharp upturn in the London me\ntal market and a moderate rise in\ndomestic commodity prices helped\nccpptrs, many investors taking the\nview' the long decline in staples might\nba near its close.\nDespite improved sentiment, tran\nsactions reached only 1,048,770 shares\ncompared with yesterday\u2019s 1.377,456.\nThe Associated Press composite aver\nage of 60 stocks advanced .9 of a\npoint to 46.0.\nBonds, like stocks, moved upward.\nWheat at Chicago finished to I*4\ncents a bushel up. corn was ahead\nto 144 cents and cotton advanced\n15 to 26 cents a bale.\nAnnouncement by the treasury\nmore than $10,000,000 in gold would\nbe shipped to France arrested the\nrecent markup of foreign currencies\nand the dollar improved generally in\nexchange transactions. Final quota\ntions for sterling were $4.99% off\n2% cents, while the French franc\nended at 3.39% cents, down .01% of\na cent.\nPublic Service of New Jersey was\nthe leading stock performer among\nutilities, finishing with a gain of\n2% points at 36. Consolidated Edison\nadded 1% at 26%, and wide frac\ntions were picked up by Electric\nPower and Light at 12%. and Ameri\ncan Waterworks 12%.\nOthers to move ahead included\nAnaconda 27%. Kennecott 31%.\nPhelps Dodge 22%, United States\nSteel 65%, National Steel 61%, Chrya\nle 69%, J. I. Case 94%, International\nHarvester 66%, Westinghouse 94%\ndu Pont 115%, Allied Chemical 157\nPhillips Petroleum 42%, Pennsylvania\nRailroad 23, Allis Chalmers 43% and\nPhillip Morris 76%.\nCall money steady; l per cent all\nday. Prime commercial paper 1. Time\nloans steady; 6 to 80 days 1%; four\nto six months 1%. Bankers\u2019 accept\nances unchanged. Rediscount rate.\nNew' York Reserve bank. 1 per cent.\nBar silver steady and unchanged\nat 44% cents an ounce.\nFollowing is a complete list of\nfinal stock transactions:\nSele* in lOO\u2019a Hijrh Low Close Chg.\nA\n3 Acres Stl 51 Vb 51 51%+ 1%\n9 Adam* Exp 10% 9% 10%+\n1 Adam* Millit 20% 20% 20%+\n4 Addressog 22% 22% 22%\n58 Air Reduction 50% 49% 49%\n1 Air-Way E! Ap 1% 1%\n14 Alaska Juneau 12% 12% 12%\n4 Alleghany Corp 1% 1% I%\u2014\n1 Do pf S3O w ,14 14 14\n1 Do pr pf 14 14 14\n5 Allegheny Steel 20 19 19\n31 Al Ch A Dye ...157 152 157 6\n1 Allied Mills 14% 14% 14%+ 1%\n19 Allied St re 10% 9% 10%+\n18 Allis Ch Mfg 43% 42% 43%+ 2%\n1 Alpha P Cere 12% 12% 12%+\n1 Amal Leather 2% 2% 2%+\n4 Amerado Corp 00% 00 60%+ 2%\n1 Am A C Del 60 60 60\n21 Am Bank Note 13% 13% 13%+\n6Am Brake Bhoe 35 34 35\nJO Am Can 86% 85 86\n7 Am Car A Fdy 21 20% 21 -4-1%\n2 Do pf 40 39 40 1\n17 Am Ch A Cable 17 10% 16%\n2 Am Colortype ..8 7% 7%\n6Am Com! Alco 14% 13% 14\n1 Am Crystal Sug 16% 16% 16%\n14 Am Encaus Til 4% 4% 4%\n33 Am A For Pow 5 4% 4%\n3 Do |0 pf 21 20% 20%+ 1%\n3 Do J 7 pf 26 25% 26+2\n10 Do 2 pf 12% 11 11%+ 1%\n9 Am Hide A Lea 4 3% 4\n2 Do pf 23 23 